<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="388" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[160,1156,362,525]" box="[160,285,362,387]" pageId="10" pageNumber="388">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,285,362,387]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="388">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[160,1156,362,525]" pageId="10" pageNumber="388">
The species is named after 
<emphasis box="[469,560,397,421]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="388">fortuitus</emphasis>
, Latin for accidental, by chance, in reference to how the 
<typeStatus box="[207,307,432,456]" pageId="10" pageNumber="388">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected. The specimen was found dead, lying on the ground, and was kept among unprepared material for almost 30 years, after which it was recognised as a new species and then pinned for study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
